  "theory": "In a series RLC circuit, resonance occurs when the inductive reactance XL equals the capacitive reactance XC. At resonance frequency fr = 1/(2π√LC), the impedance Z is minimum and purely resistive (Z = R). Current is maximum at resonance. VL and VC are equal and opposite, and may be much larger than the source voltage (voltage magnification). Quality factor Q = (1/R)√(L/C) represents the sharpness of resonance. Series resonance is used in bandpass filters, radio tuning circuits, and signal processing.",
  "keyPoints": [
    "Resonance condition: XL = XC → ωL = 1/(ωC) → fr = 1/(2π√LC)",
    "At resonance: Z = R (minimum), I = V/R (maximum), power factor = 1",
    "VL = VC = Q × Vsource (voltage magnification, Q can be >> 1)",
    "Quality factor Q = ωrL/R = 1/(omega_rCR) = (1/R)√(L/C)",
    "Bandwidth BW = fr/Q = R/L (Hz) — determines selectivity"
  ],
  "useCases": [
    "AM radio receiver tuning circuits",
    "Bandpass and bandstop filters",
    "Power factor correction in AC circuits"
  ]
